{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"ada254e2f5c7002a8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch (load them via ToolSearch query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\" first if not available). The current date is June 2026.\n\nRESEARCH ANGLE: Concrete code-capability benchmark numbers for SMALL local models (~7-8B class) vs frontier models in 2025-2026.\n\nFind concrete numbers (with source URLs) for these models on these benchmarks:\n- Models: Qwen3-8B, Qwen2.5-Coder-7B and 14B, Qwen3-Coder, DeepSeek-Coder / DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Lite, similar 7-14B local models.\n- Frontier comparison: Claude (Sonnet 3.5/3.7/4, Opus 4), GPT-4o/o1/o3/GPT-5, DeepSeek-V3/R1.\n- Benchmarks: SWE-bench Verified (% resolved), LiveCodeBench, Aider Polyglot leaderboard, HumanEval/MBPP (less important).\n\nKEY QUESTION: How far below frontier are small local 7-8B models specifically at REAL multi-file code edits that compile and pass tests (SWE-bench Verified is the key proxy)? Get the actual percentages: e.g. what does Qwen2.5-Coder-7B/14B score on SWE-bench Verified vs Claude's ~70%+ vs frontier. Note that small models often score near-zero or single digits on SWE-bench Verified without scaffolding.\n\nRun at least 4-5 searches with varied queries. Fetch the most authoritative pages (official leaderboards: swebench.com, aider.chat/docs/leaderboards, livecodebench.github.io, model release blog posts/papers, Hugging Face model cards). Cross-check numbers across sources.\n\nReturn a list of FALSIFIABLE CLAIMS, each as: the claim (with specific number), the model+benchmark, and the source URL. Flag any numbers that conflict between sources. Do NOT write files. Return findings only as your final message."},"uuid":"764b6b8e-eda7-4085-b24f-02e056986dc3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:19.059Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-e